{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fc9049f4-340d-4486-a338-4a3aae6f6674","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports the modern approach. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    // TestContext is injected via constructor (MSTest 3.3+)\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous init here (e.g., create objects, set fields)\n    }\n\n    // Async init — runs after constructor, before each test\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // await async setup (e.g., DB connections, HTTP clients)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup — runs after each test\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor** → synchronous init + `TestContext` injection (replaces the old `[TestInitialize]` for sync work).\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** → async per-test setup (replaces `[TestInitialize] async Task`).\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`** → async per-test teardown.\n- The old `TestContext` property-setter pattern still works but constructor injection is preferred in v3+.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"027c77e4-2998-41b1-8115-01a7f27b8076","outputTokens":370,"requestId":"1BC5:1BD824:CFFCF1:EB73D9:6A03D72D"},"id":"6f55f1b4-e522-4376-84ab-90b08046e604","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:43:19.601Z","parentId":"83d227c4-7f25-45ac-8b44-fce450ce90a6"}
